- [door opens]

477
00:24:14.307 --> 00:24:16.225
Have I got an update for you.

478
00:24:16.226 --> 00:24:18.936
- Do you see that. that right there?
- The exclamation point.

479
00:24:18.937 --> 00:24:24.024
That is not supposed to exist
because typewriters made before 1960s

480
00:24:24.025 --> 00:24:25.694
didn't have a one key.

481
00:24:26.778 --> 00:24:28.779
- Wait.
- No. she's right.

482
00:24:28.780 --> 00:24:32.116
I remember you would use the lowercase L.

483
00:24:32.117 --> 00:24:36.787
So. if there's no one.
there's no exclamation point either.

484
00:24:36.788 --> 00:24:41.250
Well. did the Fan get a special
plate for just one punctuation mark?

485
00:24:41.251 --> 00:24:44.962
I don't think so.
I think he used a period and an apostrophe

486
00:24:44.963 --> 00:24:48.090
and made his own exclamation plate.

487
00:24:48.091 --> 00:24:50.551
Which means he didn't
use any modern typewriter.

488
00:24:50.552 --> 00:24:54.013
And older typewriters have very limited.
you know. variety of typefaces

489
00:24:54.014 --> 00:24:56.765
which narrows down where he's getting
his building materials from.

490
00:24:56.766 --> 00:25:00.102
Not to mention the larger font. that
should make it easier to find as well.

491
00:25:00.103 --> 00:25:03.689
Mm-hmm. And even if he had
a large font typewriter.

492
00:25:03.690 --> 00:25:07.401
he'd still need to get another striker
because pathetic has two T's.

493
00:25:07.402 --> 00:25:09.695
- [clicks tongue]
- [Rossi] What's the point of all that?

494
00:25:09.696 --> 00:25:11.364
Just to call us pathetic?

495
00:25:11.990 --> 00:25:13.575
Might not be for us.

496
00:25:15.618 --> 00:25:16.745
Right.

497
00:25:18.246 --> 00:25:21.124
Right. Let's go see him.

498
00:25:24.753 --> 00:25:26.295
- Is he...
- Don't worry about him.

499
00:25:26.296 --> 00:25:27.796
What about you...

500
00:25:27.797 --> 00:25:30.424
Is that the same
outfit you wore yesterday?

501
00:25:30.425 --> 00:25:32.301
Did you go to bed last night?

502
00:25:32.302 --> 00:25:34.011
Yeah. I som...

503
00:25:34.012 --> 00:25:37.265
I don't... I'm fine.
Why do I have to change every day?

504
00:25:38.224 --> 00:25:40.268
[announcer on PA] <i>Inmates. clear the tier.</i>

505
00:25:41.227 --> 00:25:43.103
Well. he's not Mark David Chapman.

506
00:25:43.104 --> 00:25:44.521
[Prentiss] No. he's not.

507
00:25:44.522 --> 00:25:45.773
What is he then?

508
00:25:45.774 --> 00:25:47.442
A copycat of you.

509
00:25:48.234 --> 00:25:49.735
I never branded anyone.

510
00:25:49.736 --> 00:25:52.280
Ever restrained anyone
with a leather belt?

511
00:25:54.783 --> 00:25:56.617
There are three kinds of copycats.

512
00:25:56.618 --> 00:26:01.205
One who wants to learn everything
he can about the killer he's emulating.

513
00:26:01.206 --> 00:26:03.916
One who wants everyone
to think that his crimes

514
00:26:03.917 --> 00:26:06.668
are being committed
by the killer he's emulating.

515
00:26:06.669 --> 00:26:07.878
And then there's the third.

516
00:26:07.879 --> 00:26:10.964
the one who wants to be
better than his predecessor.

517
00:26:10.965 --> 00:26:12.467
Like Derek Brown. You remember him?

518
00:26:13.802 --> 00:26:15.844
Yeah. He copied Jack the Ripper.

519
00:26:15.845 --> 00:26:17.846
but they never found
the bodies of his two victims.

520
00:26:17.847 --> 00:26:20.183
so he was almost better
until they caught him.

521
00:26:22.102 --> 00:26:24.646
Studied that case
after you wrote a book about it.

522
00:26:25.647 --> 00:26:26.731
Exactly.

523
00:26:28.942 --> 00:26:31.652
Ah. I see what you're saying.

524
00:26:31.653 --> 00:26:34.405
It's almost like I'm a copycat of you.
right. Dave?

525
00:26:38.493 --> 00:26:43.914
We think the Fan is like Brown.
or the school shooter model

526
00:26:43.915 --> 00:26:47.918
inspired by the Columbine shooters.
only he's trying to surpass you.

527
00:26:47.919 --> 00:26:50.295
So. he's doing everything I did
before I started killing.

528
00:26:50.296 --> 00:26:54.425
but now he feels advanced enough
to do his own thing.

529
00:26:55.593 --> 00:26:57.636
which means it's probably isn't his first.

530
00:26:57.637 --> 00:26:59.180
That's what we thought.

531
00:26:59.764 --> 00:27:00.974
Who do you think it is?

532
00:27:04.102 --> 00:27:05.228
I don't know.

533
00:27:07.438 --> 00:27:08.565
You know.

534
00:27:10.984 --> 00:27:12.861
- No. I don't know...
- You know.

535
00:27:15.488 --> 00:27:18.032
And you've already done something.
haven't you?

536
00:27:19.492 --> 00:27:20.493
Dave.

537
00:27:21.744 --> 00:27:23.412
you said yourself.
I've grown a conscience.

538
00:27:23.413 --> 00:27:25.582
I wouldn't do anything
to jeopardize your trust.

539
00:27:28.710 --> 00:27:29.752
Yeah.

540
00:27:31.045 --> 00:27:34.007
You've studied me and I've studied you.

541
00:27:36.718 --> 00:27:41.639
So. whatever you did.
I will figure it out.

542
00:27:57.488 --> 00:27:58.489
[Brian] No.

543
00:27:59.198 --> 00:28:01.659
Yeah. all the information was in the ad.

544
00:28:03.161 --> 00:28:05.954
No. I'm not gonna drop
the price on the podcast notes.

545
00:28:05.955 --> 00:28:08.707
Do you have any idea what's in there?
Do you understand?

546
00:28:08.708 --> 00:28:10.335
They should be in the Smithsonian.

547
00:28:11.836 --> 00:28:14.630
The price is non-negotiable.

548
00:28:14.631 --> 00:28:18.258
No. I'm not gonna
throw in the podcast sign.

549
00:28:18.259 --> 00:28:20.762
Because someone's on the way
right now to buy it.

550
00:28:21.763 --> 00:28:24.598
- Okay. you listen to me. you little shit.
- [knocks on door]

551
00:28:24.599 --> 00:28:27.268
Oh. All right.
here's what I can do for you.

552
00:28:34.317 --> 00:28:35.568
Hey. Brian.

553
00:28:36.486 --> 00:28:37.569
Sheila.

554
00:28:37.570 --> 00:28:39.071
Can I come in?

555
00:28:39.072 --> 00:28:42.032
Oh... [chuckles] ...yeah. sure.

556
00:28:42.033 --> 00:28:44.785
- I wasn't expecting you.
- [both chuckle]

557
00:28:44.786 --> 00:28:47.204
- You look fantastic.
- Aw.

558
00:28:47.205 --> 00:28:49.247
- I didn't mean...
- No. no. It's okay.

559
00:28:49.248 --> 00:28:52.834
Listen. after the divorce. I could
